                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/2492: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-11-05T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 5, 1931—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 5—2:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>280. Consulate’s 272, November 2, 6 p.m. [<hi rend="italic">9 a.m</hi>.]<note
                        n="58" xml:id="d346fn58">Not printed.</note> The Secretariat has given
                    publicity to Briand’s note to Yoshizawa.<note n="59" xml:id="d346fn59">See
                        telegram No. 270, October 31, 9 a.m., from the Consul at Geneva, <ref
                            target="#pg_345">p. 345</ref>.</note> It is believed that Briand took
                    this decision with regard to publicity because he did not wish to wait longer
                    for a Japanese reply which, according to information from the Secretariat, has
                    not been received up to date.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
